{"id":295,"date":"2022-06-10T07:14:45","date_gmt":"2022-06-10T07:14:45","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/mrteck4u.com\/?p=295"},"modified":"2022-06-20T04:08:38","modified_gmt":"2022-06-20T04:08:38","slug":"what-can-music-do-for-you-interesting","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"http:\/\/mrteck4u.com\/index.php\/2022\/06\/10\/what-can-music-do-for-you-interesting\/","title":{"rendered":"what can music do to help you?"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<h2>intro<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Music can be very beneficial and helpful to you, What can music do to help you? when you are listening to it every day, in one way or another. It all depends on the type of music you listen to because there are different types of music and some types can be good for you and others bad for you. When it comes to classical music it&#8217;s been proven that people who listen to classical music on a regular basis tend to live longer because it makes them feel relaxed and calmer than any other type of music would do, in other words, you relax more and your blood pressure stays stable while listening to classical music.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Music helps with concentration<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>It&#8217;s well known that listening to classical or instrumental music for a few minutes a day is one of many scientifically proven ways to improve concentration and focus. Research shows that it works by reducing distractions. The specific type of listening used in these studies is known as passive (as opposed to active) listening, where participants just listen rather than engage with the sounds in any way. In an active-listening study led by LeMoyne College researchers, students listened passively to classical or country music while completing computer tasks; those who listened to classical performed better on subsequent tests than those who listened to country.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Music helps with your mood<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The rhythm of a song has been proven to affect our heart rate, breathing patterns, and blood pressure. This is called entrainment, and it has positive effects on your overall mood. There\u2019s some evidence that putting on calming music before going to bed may actually improve sleep quality. In one study conducted at Baylor University in Texas, researchers played soft piano music in exam rooms while people had their teeth cleaned or cavities filled. When they returned six months later for a checkup, patients reported feeling less pain and anxiety during procedures than those who hadn\u2019t listened to soothing tunes beforehand. Music helps with the thinking process: Listening helps build memories for what we hear\u2014not just lyrics but also tones and instruments used in songs.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Music helps with decision making<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Studies suggest that a simple song might be all we need to make better choices and decisions. For example, when people were asked how much they would pay for certain merchandise, more often than not, those who heard a song by their favorite artist said they\u2019d spend more money than those who didn\u2019t. Of course, there are other factors at play, but scientists think that listening to music has an effect on our neural networks; it changes our mood or biases us in some way. Scientists have even made correlations between what songs we listen to (and buy) and how we vote.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Music makes boring jobs more bearable<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>I\u2019m not talking about listening to music while working\u2014although that\u2019s certainly not a bad idea. I mean actually using it as a tool in your everyday life. If you spend most of your day at a desk, try listening to it through headphones. If you tend to listen with earbuds, try switching up your playlist and putting on your headphones so that they stay out of sight. Your coworkers will appreciate it\u2014and even if they don\u2019t, your productivity won\u2019t suffer as much as you think! A study from 2013 found that workers who listened to music were more productive than those who didn\u2019t, but only when their choice of tunes was self-selected. In other words, you should be able to choose what you want to hear without anyone else making suggestions for you. The study also found that people who listened to their own playlists were more productive than those who had no music at all\u2014even if their choices weren\u2019t particularly upbeat or peppy. Just knowing that they could pick whatever song they wanted to be made them feel better about being there and doing what they had to do, which resulted in increased performance overall.<a href=\"http:\/\/www.mrtrickx.com\">for more info visit that website<\/a><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Music enhances productivity<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Music has also been shown to enhance productivity. A number of studies have found that adding ambient music increases our performance in tasks such as math, reading comprehension, memory recall, and listening skills. When we are working hard and not taking breaks, ambient noise can distract us from our concentration. This is why many work environments don\u2019t allow for background noise; however, research shows that even simple noises like a fan or soft instrumental music can increase productivity and reduce stress. This means that if your job allows it, it\u2019s a good idea to have a radio or some kind of headphones on during work hours so you never feel tempted to break out of your workflow for silly <a href=\"http:\/\/mrteck4u.com\/index.php\/2022\/06\/19\/get-ready-america-songwriter-carin-leon-is-coming-to-a-city-near-you\/\">distractions like checking <\/a>Facebook!<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code><\/code><\/pre>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>intro Music can be very beneficial and helpful to you, What can music do to help you? when you are<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":296,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open"